thuanian Kazys, Algimantas, Stasys.","French: habitational name, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i>, denoting someone from Argis, a place in Ain, or Argy, a place in Indre. This surname is not found in France.","Lithuanian: unflattering nickname derived from <i>dargùs</i> ‘ugly, unpleasant, irritable’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gaubert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Thierry, Arnaud, Aurore, Clothilde, Irby, Jacques, Monique, Raoul, Reynald.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Gaubert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Gautberht</i>, composed of the elements <i>gaut</i>, an ethnic name meaning ‘Goth’ or ‘Geat’ (see   Goss  ), and <i>berht</i> ‘bright’.","French: variant of   Galbert   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Galbert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."]},{"name":"Goss","meanings":["Short form of   Jocelyn  , also occasionally used as an independent given name. In part it may also be a revival of a medieval boy's name (  see  Joyce  ). The name is borne by the British actor  Joss Ackland  (  b. 1928 ) and the female pop singer  Joss Stone  (  b. 1987 ) as Jocelyn Eve Stoker."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gaubert D'argies was born in 1249, in Argy, Indre, Centre-Val de Loire, France, his father, Reginald d'Argies II, was 32 and his mother, Isabelle de Clermont, was 35. He married Jeanne de Beaumont-Meulan-Gournay. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1339, in Catheux, Oise, Picardie, F